  <p class="eyebrow">OIATC · For Sagamok members</p>
  <h1>Sagamok's members-only website has not been private</h1>
  <p class="lede">Our members-only documents, including Council minutes, have been <span class="hlw">readable by anyone on the internet, with no login</span>. Here is what that means, in plain terms, and how you can see it for yourself.</p>
  <p class="byline">From Russell Jones, a Sagamok Anishnawbek member, for the Ontario Indigenous AI and Technology Council. <!--EDIT DATE-->May 31, 2026.</p>

  <div class="summary">
    <p class="h">In short</p>
    <ul>
      <li>The Sagamok members-only website has been serving its documents <span class="hlw">to anyone online, with no account and no password</span>.</li>
      <li>The login screen you see <strong>only works for a person clicking in a web browser</strong>. To a search engine or an AI system it is not there at all, which is why these documents already turn up in web searches and can be pulled into AI tools.</li>
      <li>It is not just the meeting minutes. Most of the members-only area is affected, including financial statements and treaty settlement documents.</li>
      <li>I raised this through the proper channels before and was told there was no problem. This time I am telling members directly.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2>See it for yourself</h2>
  <p>You do not have to take my word for any of this. Search "sagamok meeting minutes" in any search engine. Our members-only minutes come up as a normal result. Open it, and for a second you can see the page before a login screen drops over the top.</p>
  <p>That one second is the proof. The page was <span class="hl">already sent to your device before the login appeared</span>. You do not need an account or a password. <span class="hlw">Anyone can do this right now.</span></p>

  <h2>Why the login does not protect anything</h2>
  <p>When you open one of these pages, the full document is sent to your device first. A moment later, a small program inside your web browser covers it with a login screen.</p>
  <p class="pull">The lock was never on the door. It was a curtain, pulled across a room that was already open.</p>
  <p>A search engine, or anyone who is not a person clicking through a browser, never sees the curtain. It just takes the page. That is how our minutes ended up sitting in search results, where I found them.</p>

  <figure class="diagram">
    <svg viewBox="0 0 680 214" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" role="img" aria-label="A browser is shown the page then a login covers it, while a search engine keeps the whole page with no login.">
