    </svg>
    <figcaption class="figcap">Top: what a member sees, the page appears, then a login covers it. Bottom: what a search engine, an AI tool, or anyone not using a browser gets, the whole page with no login at all.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>Some of the files were given their own password on top of this. That does not help either, because <span class="hlw">the password is printed in plain sight on the same public page as the file</span>, a page that itself opens with no login. A non-member reads the password the same way they reach the file. It is a lock with the key taped beside it.</p>

  <h2>It is not just the minutes</h2>
  <p>The same problem runs across the members-only area as a whole. Most of those sections served their content to anyone with no login, including the Nation's <span class="hl">annual audited financial statements</span>, the <span class="hl">Robinson Huron Treaty settlement and trust-distribution documents</span>, and <span class="hl">family-services material</span>.</p>
  <p>The only part built correctly is the personal My Account page, which shows your information only after you actually sign in. To be clear about what I did: I confirmed which sections were open, but <strong>I did not download anyone's documents, and I have not shared any of this material.</strong></p>

  <p>For how the hosting works and where your data goes, who touches it, where the files physically live, and which laws reach them, see the companion explainer: <a href="/explainers/where-your-data-lives">Where does your community's data actually live?</a></p>

  <h2>Where this ends up: search engines and AI</h2>
  <p>An open page does not just sit there quietly. Because there is no login in front of it, anything that reads the web can take a copy.</p>
  <p><span class="hl">Search engines</span> have already copied these pages, which is how they show up in a web search. <span class="hl">AI systems read the open web too.</span> An AI assistant that answers questions by looking things up can repeat this material when someone asks about Sagamok, and the companies that build AI models send out crawlers that copy public pages to train on. The site does nothing to stop them.</p>
  <p class="pull">A search result can be taken down. Information already pulled into an AI model is far harder, often impossible, to take back.</p>
  <p>For a community, this is the heart of it. <span class="hlw">Our private information is flowing into systems we do not own or control.</span> That is the exact problem this council exists to work on: keeping Indigenous data in Indigenous hands.</p>

  <h2>The timeline: I raised this years ago</h2>
  <p>This is not a surprise I am springing on the community. I have raised concerns about this system before, with real dates on the record. I am naming offices and dates, not individuals.</p>
  <div class="timeline">
    <div class="tl"><p class="when">September 3, 2023</p><p>I wrote to the office of the Chief raising concerns about how member data was being collected and handled on the website, and offered to help move it to a safer setup.</p></div>
    <div class="tl"><p class="when">September 7, 2023</p><p>The Council Secretariat replied, acknowledged the concern about the members-only portal, and said it would be brought to Council.</p></div>
    <div class="tl"><p class="when">February 6, 2026</p><p>When all members were told to reset their portal passwords, I asked the IT office in writing whether there had been any breach or security problem. The same-day written reply stated there had been no security issues and no vulnerability to member accounts or personal data.</p></div>
    <div class="tl"><p class="when">May 31, 2026</p><p>While building a community resource for members, I found that the members-only documents were being served to anyone online. Raising concerns quietly had not worked before, so this time I am bringing it to members directly. The full technical detail is documented and available to the band to verify and fix.</p></div>
  </div>

  <h2>What needs to happen</h2>
  <p>The website has to be changed so the <span class="hl">login is checked on the server, before any document is sent</span>, not painted over afterward in the browser. Because these pages have already been copied into search engines, they also have to be <span class="hl">removed from search results</span>, not just fixed on the site. The site should also <span class="hl">block the AI crawlers it currently allows</span>, and we should assume some of this material is already inside AI systems and search caches, where it cannot simply be deleted.</p>
  <p>The bigger lesson is the one that matters most. When the systems holding our information are run on outside platforms by people outside the community, and we do not have our own qualified people able to check them, we cannot answer a simple question: is our data safe, and who can see it. <strong>Our data is ours.</strong> Deciding how it is kept, and being able to check it ourselves, is part of our <span class="hl">sovereignty</span>.</p>

  <h2>What happens now</h2>
  <!-- EDIT this line to match reality at publish time. -->
  <p class="status">I raised concerns about this system through the proper channels in 2023 and again in February 2026, and was told there was no problem. This time I am telling members directly rather than waiting on those channels again. The full technical detail is documented and available to Chief and Council and the IT office so it can be verified and fixed. Members are welcome to ask Chief and Council and the IT office directly whether their information was affected.</p>

  <p class="tech"><b>For anyone technical:</b> an anonymous web request, sent with no account and no password, returns these files directly with a normal success response, and the members index page returns its full contents the same way. The site's rules place no restriction on AI crawlers. The complete method and the captured proof are set out in a technical report available to Chief and Council. No member documents were downloaded to establish any of this; the proof is response information and the site's own public files.</p>

  <footer>
    <p>This is from Russell Jones, a Sagamok Anishnawbek member, on behalf of the Ontario Indigenous AI and Technology Council. It is independent of Sagamok Chief and Council and its administration. I have not shared any of the affected documents. Questions and corrections are welcome.</p>
    <p class="kicker">Ontario Indigenous AI &amp; Technology Council · OIATC · oiatc.ca</p>
